<DOC><DOCNO> AP890307-0167 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 2102EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Somalia-Prisoners     03-07 0218</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Somalia-Prisoners,220</SECOND><HEAD>Ridge Says Somalia Grants Amnesty for Architect, 20 Other Prisoners</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Somalia has granted amnesty to 21 people andreleased them from prison, including an architect whose jailing hadprompted protests by lawmakers and his former American classmates,Rep. Thomas Ridge, R-Pa., said Tuesday.   Ridge released a copy of a letter dated Monday to Frank Light, ofthe State Department, from Abdullahi A. Addou, Somali ambassador tothe United States.   The letter said that the Somali president ``has granted amnestyto the following people and they are free from prison,'' and listed21 prisoners, including Sulieman Nuh Ali. Ali's case has beeninvestigated by Amnesty International, the London-based human rightsgroup that had classified him as a ``prisoner of conscience.''   According to Ridge, Ali was held without charges since 1982 andthen was found guilty of treason last year.   Ali, 45, attended Pennsylvania's Allegheny College in themid-1960s before transferring to Howard University and earning adegree in architecture and urban planning.   He took a job with the Somalia Ministry of Public Works buildinglow-cost housing for workers, then went into business for himself.   A former classmate helped launch a student petition drive at thePennsylvania school, and 28 House and Senate members recently sent atelegram of protest to the Somali president.</TEXT></DOC>